The dispute between supporters of Governor Hope Uzodinma and his predecessor, Rochas Okorocha over the leadership of the All Progressives Congress (APC) in Imo State will end on May 27 when the Supreme Court is scheduled to render its judgment. A five-member panel of the court led by Justice Olukayode Ariwoola chose the date after entertaining final submissions from lawyers representing parties. The marked: SC/CV/884/2020 filed by the APC has as respondents, Evan Ewerem, Adams Oshionhole and Daniel Nwanfor (Dan Nwanfor), whose leadership is being challenged by some members loyal to Uzodinma. Nwanfor, believed to be loyal to Rochas Okorocha, has been adjudged the actual Chairman of the Imo APC in the judgment by the High Court of the Federal Capital Territory (FCT), a decision that was upheld by the Court of Appeal, Abuja, promoting the current appeal by members loyal to the incumbent Governor.   BREAKING: APC March 26 convention date stands – Bagudu     ‘Transport fare smallest gift a man can give women’     BREAKING: Senate passes bills on LGA financial,…   While making his final submissions on Monday, the appellant’s lawyer, Robert Emmukpoeruo (SAN) urged the court to allow the appeal. Emmukpoeruo further urged the court to set aside the judgment of the Court of Appeal, which among others, affirmed Nwanfor’s leadership of the Imo APC. Nwanfor’s lawyer, Chidozie Ogundi, prayed the court to hold in favour of his client, affirm the decision of the Court of Appeal and dismiss the appeal. The dispute started in 2018 when the APC in Imo State conducted ward and Local Government congress to constitute its leadership.